      "content": "Here are some of the strongest philosophical arguments supporting the idea that internet regulation is a violation of free speech:\n\n• John Locke's \"Laissez-Faire\" Principle: Individuals have inherent rights to pursue their own interests and express themselves freely, untainted by government interference.\n• Carl Schmitt's \"State Sovereignty\" theory: The state has authority to regulate the internet in service of maintaining order and security, potentially infringing on individual rights to free expression.\n• Immanuel Kant's \"Universalizability\" principle: Regulations that restrict internet freedom may be morally wrong if they could be used to justify similar restrictions on other fundamental rights, leading to a slippery slope.\n• Jean-Jacques Rousseau's concept of the \"Social Contract\": Government regulation of the internet may be seen as an overreach of authority, as individuals may not have explicitly consented to such restrictions.\n• Ayn Rand's \"Objectivism\": Government regulation of the internet is antithetical to the principles of individual rights and property, as it interferes with the freedom to pursue one's own interests and values.",
